00:51:35.960 --> 00:51:38.630 align:middle line:90%
32 months-- it's unbelievable.

00:51:38.630 --> 00:51:41.510 align:middle line:84%
And we also get
deposits and withdrawals

00:51:41.510 --> 00:51:42.770 align:middle line:90%
measured in the data.

00:51:42.770 --> 00:51:44.450 align:middle line:84%
That's a lot of
detail to absorb.

00:51:44.450 --> 00:51:48.230 align:middle line:84%
Let me show you what's
going on in the model.

00:51:48.230 --> 00:51:50.660 align:middle line:90%
We estimate the cash flow.

00:51:50.660 --> 00:51:54.530 align:middle line:84%
We recover all the
parameters that we need,

00:51:54.530 --> 00:51:57.920 align:middle line:84%
take a stand on the
interest rate in the bank,

00:51:57.920 --> 00:52:01.900 align:middle line:84%
and then look at how small
or big the cost would be.

00:52:01.900 --> 00:52:05.060 align:middle line:90%
b is varying down here.

00:52:05.060 --> 00:52:09.980 align:middle line:84%
And the consequences for
currency, especially but also

00:52:09.980 --> 00:52:12.360 align:middle line:90%
withdrawals and deposits.

00:52:12.360 --> 00:52:16.100 align:middle line:84%
So taking the reality to be
the calibrated expenditure

00:52:16.100 --> 00:52:19.840 align:middle line:84%
flows we see in the data, along
with the few other reasonable

00:52:19.840 --> 00:52:22.660 align:middle line:84%
assumptions, I assure
you we can look

00:52:22.660 --> 00:52:25.150 align:middle line:84%
at how much cash they
should be holding relative

00:52:25.150 --> 00:52:26.140 align:middle line:90%
to consumption.

00:52:26.140 --> 00:52:27.910 align:middle line:90%
That's this blue line.

00:52:27.910 --> 00:52:32.690 align:middle line:84%
And we can barely
get it up to three.

00:52:32.690 --> 00:52:35.150 align:middle line:90%
The number in the data is 32.

00:52:35.150 --> 00:52:38.840 align:middle line:84%
I mean, you could imagine
increasing those costs

00:52:38.840 --> 00:52:40.690 align:middle line:90%
and decreasing the interest.

00:52:40.690 --> 00:52:45.800 align:middle line:84%
And this is like asymptoting
out to something flat.

00:52:45.800 --> 00:52:48.590 align:middle line:84%
So you end up with
something ridiculous.

00:52:48.590 --> 00:52:50.150 align:middle line:90%
The model isn't working.

00:52:50.150 --> 00:52:53.275 align:middle line:84%
You don't go to the bank
and forego two years

00:52:53.275 --> 00:52:54.650 align:middle line:84%
worth of consumption
while you're

00:52:54.650 --> 00:52:57.110 align:middle line:90%
doing your banking transection.

00:52:57.110 --> 00:52:59.540 align:middle line:84%
It's just not a
reasonable value.

00:52:59.540 --> 00:53:02.510 align:middle line:90%
The sign makes sense.

00:53:02.510 --> 00:53:06.140 align:middle line:84%
The higher the cost,
b, of going to the bank

00:53:06.140 --> 00:53:09.750 align:middle line:84%
to either withdraw or deposit,
the less you're going to do it.

00:53:09.750 --> 00:53:12.830 align:middle line:84%
So when you do it, the
transactions are bigger.

00:53:12.830 --> 00:53:15.515 align:middle line:84%
And meanwhile, you're
holding more cash.

00:53:15.515 --> 00:53:19.700 align:middle line:84%
If b goes to infinity,
then it's all in cash.

00:53:19.700 --> 00:53:21.008 align:middle line:90%
Forget the bank.

00:53:21.008 --> 00:53:22.550 align:middle line:84%
And when you go
rarely, then you have

00:53:22.550 --> 00:53:24.510 align:middle line:90%
to make up a big difference.

00:53:24.510 --> 00:53:26.450 align:middle line:84%
And this is the
frequency, which again,

00:53:26.450 --> 00:53:29.540 align:middle line:84%
as b goes up, the frequency
of going to the bank

00:53:29.540 --> 00:53:31.010 align:middle line:90%
is going down.

00:53:31.010 --> 00:53:36.710 align:middle line:84%
Question-- so because we
did that life cycle planner,

00:53:36.710 --> 00:53:40.760 align:middle line:84%
we wanted to evaluate as a
randomized controlled trial

00:53:40.760 --> 00:53:44.730 align:middle line:84%
how well or poorly it was
working, and in the process,

00:53:44.730 --> 00:53:48.170 align:middle line:84%
we gathered monthly data
for the urban household.

00:53:48.170 --> 00:53:50.330 align:middle line:84%
So we're not in
villages anymore.

00:53:50.330 --> 00:53:53.780 align:middle line:84%
We're in towns or even
city neighborhoods.

00:53:53.780 --> 00:53:57.110 align:middle line:84%
In each of the four
provinces, we basically

00:53:57.110 --> 00:53:59.910 align:middle line:84%
replicated all the
existing surveys.

00:53:59.910 --> 00:54:02.430 align:middle line:84%
So the same questions
are being asked.

00:54:02.430 --> 00:54:04.430 align:middle line:84%
And this is kind of
buried here, but if you

00:54:04.430 --> 00:54:08.420 align:middle line:84%
look at the normalized cash
in terms of consumption

00:54:08.420 --> 00:54:12.800 align:middle line:84%
for the urban sample,
and look over here,

00:54:12.800 --> 00:54:16.280 align:middle line:90%
we got a number of 3.87--

00:54:16.280 --> 00:54:17.420 align:middle line:90%
much closer to 3.

00:54:17.420 --> 00:54:19.070 align:middle line:90%
Nothing like the 37.

00:54:19.070 --> 00:54:21.890 align:middle line:84%
Well, actually, I should
be over here at the median.

00:54:21.890 --> 00:54:23.630 align:middle line:90%
So it's 1.94.

00:54:23.630 --> 00:54:25.760 align:middle line:84%
But when we do some
adjustments in the data,

00:54:25.760 --> 00:54:29.200 align:middle line:84%
I'm happy to tell
you about them.

00:54:29.200 --> 00:54:31.660 align:middle line:84%
That's within
reach of the model.

00:54:31.660 --> 00:54:37.360 align:middle line:84%
We calibrate the model again
using the cash statistics--

00:54:37.360 --> 00:54:40.240 align:middle line:84%
the zapping, big
shock, small shock,

00:54:40.240 --> 00:54:42.640 align:middle line:84%
how often they happen,
et cetera et cetera,

00:54:42.640 --> 00:54:44.350 align:middle line:90%
and get a model prediction.

00:54:44.350 --> 00:54:48.310 align:middle line:84%
And the implied
value, m, depending

00:54:48.310 --> 00:54:50.740 align:middle line:84%
on whether you use the
mean or the median,

00:54:50.740 --> 00:54:55.330 align:middle line:84%
is something like 2,
which is close to what

00:54:55.330 --> 00:54:56.990 align:middle line:90%
we're getting in the data.

00:54:56.990 --> 00:54:58.870 align:middle line:84%
So now we're in
kind of business,

00:54:58.870 --> 00:55:02.170 align:middle line:84%
in the sense that a reasonable
economic model is actually

00:55:02.170 --> 00:55:05.230 align:middle line:84%
predicting pretty well how
much cash they're holding.

00:55:05.230 --> 00:55:07.840 align:middle line:84%
Whereas, in the rural
data it was a disaster.

00:55:07.840 --> 00:55:08.950 align:middle line:90%
We didn't get close.

00:55:08.950 --> 00:55:15.040 align:middle line:84%
So now we switch into how
can we understand the error

00:55:15.040 --> 00:55:18.580 align:middle line:84%
that the households are making
with their cash management?

00:55:18.580 --> 00:55:19.930 align:middle line:90%
And the guess is--

00:55:19.930 --> 00:55:21.190 align:middle line:90%
several guesses.

00:55:21.190 --> 00:55:24.130 align:middle line:84%
Some turned out to be
correct and some not.

00:55:24.130 --> 00:55:26.950 align:middle line:84%
So why would cash
holdings be so much lower

00:55:26.950 --> 00:55:29.800 align:middle line:84%
in the urban area relative
to the rural area?

00:55:29.800 --> 00:55:32.680 align:middle line:84%
Is it because households
in the urban survey deposit

00:55:32.680 --> 00:55:34.990 align:middle line:90%
more often in larger amounts?

00:55:34.990 --> 00:55:38.410 align:middle line:84%
Or is it because they withdraw
in the urban areas less

00:55:38.410 --> 00:55:40.790 align:middle line:90%
and withdraw smaller amounts?

00:55:40.790 --> 00:55:44.890 align:middle line:84%
So for deposits, it turns out
households in the rural area

00:55:44.890 --> 00:55:49.020 align:middle line:84%
deposit more and not less, and
they deposit larger amounts.

00:55:49.020 --> 00:55:51.160 align:middle line:84%
So this is exactly
the opposite of what

00:55:51.160 --> 00:55:54.280 align:middle line:84%
we would have predicted because
the cash is going into the bank

00:55:54.280 --> 00:55:56.360 align:middle line:90%
or into the local money market.

00:55:56.360 --> 00:55:58.480 align:middle line:84%
However, for
withdrawals, it works

00:55:58.480 --> 00:56:00.610 align:middle line:84%
the way we would
have conjectured,

00:56:00.610 --> 00:56:02.860 align:middle line:84%
that when urban households
put money in the bank

00:56:02.860 --> 00:56:04.720 align:middle line:84%
they don't withdraw
it very often,

00:56:04.720 --> 00:56:06.760 align:middle line:90%
and they withdraw a lot less.

00:56:06.760 --> 00:56:09.940 align:middle line:84%
It almost looks like
they're putting their proxy

00:56:09.940 --> 00:56:11.710 align:middle line:90%
for their salary into the bank.

00:56:11.710 --> 00:56:15.160 align:middle line:84%
And any other money which they
have, from business and so on,

00:56:15.160 --> 00:56:17.200 align:middle line:84%
goes into the bank
and stays there.

00:56:17.200 --> 00:56:19.960 align:middle line:84%
They just withdraw what
they need for consumption,

00:56:19.960 --> 00:56:22.990 align:middle line:84%
taking a, quote unquote,
salary equivalent out

00:56:22.990 --> 00:56:24.440 align:middle line:90%
and leaving the rest in.

00:56:24.440 --> 00:56:28.420 align:middle line:84%
So this is why their
money value's a lot lower.

00:56:28.420 --> 00:56:32.290 align:middle line:84%
There's still something to fix,
which just like in life cycle

00:56:32.290 --> 00:56:36.790 align:middle line:84%
planner, we could create from
the research cash flow app

00:56:36.790 --> 00:56:40.430 align:middle line:84%
and put it on the phone and tell
households how to manage it.

00:56:40.430 --> 00:56:43.030 align:middle line:84%
And, in fact, the
question is, why are they

00:56:43.030 --> 00:56:44.410 align:middle line:90%
having cash at all?

00:56:44.410 --> 00:56:46.690 align:middle line:84%
Why don't they just put
it on their cell phone?

00:56:46.690 --> 00:56:49.130 align:middle line:90%
And that brings us to--

00:56:49.130 --> 00:56:49.630 align:middle line:90%
oh.

00:56:49.630 --> 00:56:53.560 align:middle line:84%
And the costs of
mismanagement of currency

00:56:53.560 --> 00:56:56.530 align:middle line:84%
are very high--
something like 9 and 1/2%

00:56:56.530 --> 00:56:58.510 align:middle line:90%
of monthly consumption.

00:56:58.510 --> 00:57:00.760 align:middle line:90%
That's huge in economics.

00:57:00.760 --> 00:57:02.290 align:middle line:90%
Say, exaggerate a bit--

00:57:02.290 --> 00:57:04.630 align:middle line:90%
10, or call it 5 if you want.

00:57:04.630 --> 00:57:08.170 align:middle line:84%
5% of monthly consumption
could be saved or used

00:57:08.170 --> 00:57:11.600 align:middle line:84%
for consumption if they just
managed their currency better.

00:57:11.600 --> 00:57:13.300 align:middle line:90%
So one way to put this--

00:57:13.300 --> 00:57:17.800 align:middle line:84%
enormous cost of
mismanagement of petty cash.

00:57:17.800 --> 00:57:20.650 align:middle line:84%
Businesses get cash
advisory services.

00:57:20.650 --> 00:57:22.340 align:middle line:90%
They pay for it.

00:57:22.340 --> 00:57:24.670 align:middle line:84%
Why should these poor
households not have access

00:57:24.670 --> 00:57:26.950 align:middle line:90%
to better management tools?

00:57:26.950 --> 00:57:27.490 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:57:27.490 --> 00:57:28.390 align:middle line:90%
Sorry.

00:57:28.390 --> 00:57:29.680 align:middle line:90%
That's my view.

00:57:29.680 --> 00:57:30.910 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:57:30.910 --> 00:57:32.450 align:middle line:90%
Go to Sweden.

00:57:32.450 --> 00:57:34.750 align:middle line:84%
How much paper currency
are they using?

00:57:34.750 --> 00:57:35.890 align:middle line:90%
Close to nothing.

00:57:35.890 --> 00:57:37.360 align:middle line:90%
They're gone-- it's gone.

00:57:37.360 --> 00:57:43.090 align:middle line:84%
This is the amount of currency
relative to GDP ever-declining.

00:57:43.090 --> 00:57:46.450 align:middle line:84%
This is the absolute
level of cash,

00:57:46.450 --> 00:57:50.180 align:middle line:84%
going down in an absolute
not only relative basis.

00:57:50.180 --> 00:57:53.080 align:middle line:84%
So I got this and this
slide from the governor

00:57:53.080 --> 00:57:56.230 align:middle line:90%
of the Riksbank in Sweden.

00:57:56.230 --> 00:57:58.820 align:middle line:84%
So I don't know whether you
will appreciate the humor here.

00:57:58.820 --> 00:58:00.940 align:middle line:84%
But this is a
picture of a stone.

00:58:00.940 --> 00:58:03.820 align:middle line:84%
So economists and others
have written books

00:58:03.820 --> 00:58:07.720 align:middle line:84%
about the first coins,
the first use of cash,

00:58:07.720 --> 00:58:10.090 align:middle line:84%
and there were claims on
stones that were buried

00:58:10.090 --> 00:58:11.440 align:middle line:90%
at the bottom of the lake.

00:58:11.440 --> 00:58:14.620 align:middle line:84%
So now in Sweden, they're
transferring the stone around

00:58:14.620 --> 00:58:15.550 align:middle line:90%
on their cell phone.

00:58:15.550 --> 00:58:16.900 align:middle line:90%
Well, not really.

00:58:16.900 --> 00:58:18.940 align:middle line:90%
It's Swish, basically.

00:58:18.940 --> 00:58:22.630 align:middle line:84%
They have a bank account,
and for no money at all

00:58:22.630 --> 00:58:26.810 align:middle line:84%
households can transfer cash
to each other, buy things,

00:58:26.810 --> 00:58:27.800 align:middle line:90%
and so on.

00:58:27.800 --> 00:58:29.740 align:middle line:84%
And it's replaced
the paper currency.

00:58:29.740 --> 00:58:32.290 align:middle line:84%
It's actually a bit of a
concern for them, which

00:58:32.290 --> 00:58:34.900 align:middle line:84%
is why they're thinking
if there's no paper

00:58:34.900 --> 00:58:37.300 align:middle line:84%
currency other than
reserves, there's

00:58:37.300 --> 00:58:40.090 align:middle line:90%
no role for the central bank.

00:58:40.090 --> 00:58:44.020 align:middle line:84%
So they feel they should
be providing a payment

00:58:44.020 --> 00:58:45.280 align:middle line:90%
service as a backup.

00:58:45.280 --> 00:58:48.610 align:middle line:84%
So they're going to create,
almost surely, a central bank

00:58:48.610 --> 00:58:49.910 align:middle line:90%
digital currency.

00:58:49.910 --> 00:58:52.240 align:middle line:84%
So households will
have digital accounts

00:58:52.240 --> 00:58:55.810 align:middle line:84%
in the central bank, which is
what South Africa is doing.

00:58:55.810 --> 00:58:58.810 align:middle line:84%
China has a different
version of it and so on.

00:58:58.810 --> 00:59:01.060 align:middle line:90%
This happened in the Bahamas.

00:59:01.060 --> 00:59:03.580 align:middle line:84%
They created something
called the Sand Dollar.

00:59:03.580 --> 00:59:05.770 align:middle line:84%
The virus is
accelerating this problem

00:59:05.770 --> 00:59:08.050 align:middle line:84%
because people need
government aid,

00:59:08.050 --> 00:59:09.730 align:middle line:90%
and they can't get the aid--

00:59:09.730 --> 00:59:11.740 align:middle line:84%
truck the paper
currency over there.

00:59:11.740 --> 00:59:15.280 align:middle line:84%
When this disastrous Hurricane
Dorian destroyed an island

00:59:15.280 --> 00:59:18.590 align:middle line:84%
in the Bahamas, they couldn't
get emergency assistance.

00:59:18.590 --> 00:59:21.070 align:middle line:84%
So these are things that are
happening all over the world

00:59:21.070 --> 00:59:22.120 align:middle line:90%
right now.

00:59:22.120 --> 00:59:24.610 align:middle line:90%
This last slide is Kenya.

00:59:24.610 --> 00:59:27.490 align:middle line:84%
And I mentioned they have
two kinds of currency.

00:59:27.490 --> 00:59:30.750 align:middle line:84%
One is Kenyan shillings--
used to be a British colony.

00:59:30.750 --> 00:59:34.350 align:middle line:84%
And the other is
e-credits at Safaricom,

00:59:34.350 --> 00:59:36.330 align:middle line:90%
which is a cell phone provider.

00:59:36.330 --> 00:59:38.880 align:middle line:84%
So what you do is you
take your shillings,

00:59:38.880 --> 00:59:41.640 align:middle line:90%
you go to this Safaricom agent.

00:59:41.640 --> 00:59:45.030 align:middle line:84%
You give him your
Fiat money, and you

00:59:45.030 --> 00:59:48.690 align:middle line:84%
get credited cell
accounts called M-Pesa.

00:59:48.690 --> 00:59:51.180 align:middle line:84%
And then you can use
that to give to your mom

00:59:51.180 --> 00:59:54.540 align:middle line:84%
back in the village, who
goes to the agent there

00:59:54.540 --> 00:59:56.940 align:middle line:84%
and transfers it back
out into shillings,

00:59:56.940 --> 00:59:58.960 align:middle line:90%
or you can buy stuff.

00:59:58.960 --> 01:00:02.530 align:middle line:84%
So here you see the use
of the paper currency,

01:00:02.530 --> 01:00:06.840 align:middle line:84%
but also this e-currency,
which is created by Safaricom.

01:00:06.840 --> 01:00:09.300 align:middle line:84%
And it has reached
almost everybody.

01:00:09.300 --> 01:00:10.830 align:middle line:90%
Some economies try to do this.

01:00:10.830 --> 01:00:12.330 align:middle line:90%
We kind of tried in Thailand.

01:00:12.330 --> 01:00:14.340 align:middle line:90%
I have not yet succeeded.

01:00:14.340 --> 01:00:17.760 align:middle line:84%
In Kenya, even the
lowest income quartile--

01:00:17.760 --> 01:00:19.890 align:middle line:90%
we need to update this graph.

01:00:19.890 --> 01:00:21.900 align:middle line:90%
Tavneet Suri did this.

01:00:21.900 --> 01:00:26.250 align:middle line:84%
Roughly, 85% of the
low-income population,

01:00:26.250 --> 01:00:29.730 align:middle line:84%
and a similar, higher number
for those with no bank accounts,

01:00:29.730 --> 01:00:31.860 align:middle line:90%
are using Safaricom.

01:00:31.860 --> 01:00:33.610 align:middle line:84%
With no bank accounts--
in other words,

01:00:33.610 --> 01:00:37.020 align:middle line:84%
you don't need the traditional
legacy infrastructure.

01:00:37.020 --> 01:00:41.640 align:middle line:84%
And this is, again, the allure,
the so-called disintermediation

01:00:41.640 --> 01:00:44.340 align:middle line:84%
that the fintechs are
bringing to the world.

01:00:44.340 --> 01:00:47.310 align:middle line:84%
Of course, the commercial
bankers don't like it much.

01:00:47.310 --> 01:00:48.900 align:middle line:90%
We talked about risk-sharing.

01:00:48.900 --> 01:00:53.700 align:middle line:84%
And Tavneet and her
co-author, Billy Jack,

01:00:53.700 --> 01:00:58.710 align:middle line:84%
looked at how much consumption
is being smooth in Kenya,

01:00:58.710 --> 01:01:00.840 align:middle line:84%
comparing households
who have not yet

01:01:00.840 --> 01:01:04.440 align:middle line:84%
gotten early on the M-Pesa
expansion versus those

01:01:04.440 --> 01:01:05.430 align:middle line:90%
that did.

01:01:05.430 --> 01:01:09.640 align:middle line:84%
And there's a lot more
smoother consumption,

01:01:09.640 --> 01:01:11.070 align:middle line:84%
which you see these
common themes.

01:01:11.070 --> 01:01:12.330 align:middle line:90%
We did risk-sharing.

01:01:12.330 --> 01:01:14.910 align:middle line:84%
We did gift giving
in Thai villages.

01:01:14.910 --> 01:01:20.370 align:middle line:84%
Now people are giving gifts
and transfers through M-Pesa.

01:01:20.370 --> 01:01:22.726 align:middle line:90%
And so it has an impact.

01:01:22.726 --> 01:01:24.100 align:middle line:90%
Well, what's the big deal?

01:01:24.100 --> 01:01:26.910 align:middle line:90%
It's a big deal for Kenya.

01:01:26.910 --> 01:01:28.830 align:middle line:84%
Sweden already has
this infrastructure.

01:01:28.830 --> 01:01:30.800 align:middle line:90%
It's not a big deal.

01:01:30.800 --> 01:01:33.590 align:middle line:84%
But it makes a big deal
for low-income countries.

01:01:33.590 --> 01:01:36.440 align:middle line:84%
There are some
qualifications, though.

01:01:36.440 --> 01:01:39.090 align:middle line:84%
First of all, it's not
on a distributed ledger.

01:01:39.090 --> 01:01:43.310 align:middle line:84%
So you have to trust Safaricom
to keep the accounts properly,

01:01:43.310 --> 01:01:45.030 align:middle line:90%
and they have the cash.

01:01:45.030 --> 01:01:47.690 align:middle line:84%
So they're supposed to put
it in a commercial bank.

01:01:47.690 --> 01:01:50.010 align:middle line:90%
You trust them to do that.

01:01:50.010 --> 01:01:53.570 align:middle line:84%
So you have to rely on a
third-party vendor in Kenya.

01:01:53.570 --> 01:01:55.550 align:middle line:84%
Not only that, the
money's in the bank,

01:01:55.550 --> 01:01:57.050 align:middle line:90%
and Kenya is subject to runs.

01:01:57.050 --> 01:01:58.998 align:middle line:90%
So how safe is that?

01:01:58.998 --> 01:02:01.040 align:middle line:84%
You may think you're going
to get the money back,

01:02:01.040 --> 01:02:02.780 align:middle line:90%
but will you really?

01:02:02.780 --> 01:02:05.870 align:middle line:84%
And in other economies, they
don't have that kind of trust,

01:02:05.870 --> 01:02:08.370 align:middle line:90%
so it doesn't take off.

01:02:08.370 --> 01:02:13.070 align:middle line:84%
The other thing is those
agents, these guys,

01:02:13.070 --> 01:02:14.950 align:middle line:90%
they run out of stuff.

01:02:14.950 --> 01:02:16.870 align:middle line:84%
So you go and take
your shillings

01:02:16.870 --> 01:02:18.580 align:middle line:90%
and say I want M-Pesa.

01:02:18.580 --> 01:02:21.160 align:middle line:90%
And they can't create it.

01:02:21.160 --> 01:02:22.780 align:middle line:90%
There's no net creation.

01:02:22.780 --> 01:02:24.340 align:middle line:84%
It has to be a
one-to-one transfer.

01:02:24.340 --> 01:02:26.510 align:middle line:84%
They have to have it in
their accounts already.

01:02:26.510 --> 01:02:28.180 align:middle line:84%
And if don't have
it in the account,

01:02:28.180 --> 01:02:30.610 align:middle line:84%
they've got to say, well,
wait, or come back tomorrow.

01:02:30.610 --> 01:02:32.830 align:middle line:84%
Likewise, and perhaps
more obviously

01:02:32.830 --> 01:02:36.880 align:middle line:84%
for the currency withdrawal,
say here's my cell account.

01:02:36.880 --> 01:02:37.990 align:middle line:90%
I want to cash it out.

01:02:37.990 --> 01:02:40.165 align:middle line:84%
Oh, I don't have that
cash in my drawer.

01:02:40.165 --> 01:02:43.900 align:middle line:84%
What Tavneet discovered is
these agents are kind of linked

01:02:43.900 --> 01:02:46.420 align:middle line:84%
to each other in an
informal money market,

01:02:46.420 --> 01:02:48.280 align:middle line:84%
